And, uh, really,
we are strangers.

367
00:17:09,529 --> 00:17:11,464
I mean, we've never
even met before.

368
00:17:11,697 --> 00:17:13,165
Yeah, we did.

369
00:17:13,699 --> 00:17:15,361
You don't remember?

370
00:17:16,536 --> 00:17:18,835
Sorry, no. Where did we meet?

371
00:17:18,905 --> 00:17:20,669
We met in Cold Spring.

372
00:17:24,143 --> 00:17:29,639
Wow. I haven't thought
about Cold Spring in years.

373
00:17:29,715 --> 00:17:31,727
We used to go there on the
weekends. There was this dock.

374
00:17:31,751 --> 00:17:34,186
My sister and I would jump
off and we thought we were,

375
00:17:34,253 --> 00:17:35,812
you know,

376
00:17:35,888 --> 00:17:37,686
cliff divers. We loved it.

377
00:17:38,090 --> 00:17:39,558
Yeah, I know.

378
00:17:39,825 --> 00:17:41,623
That's, uh...

379
00:17:41,694 --> 00:17:43,253
That's where I saw you.

380
00:17:43,563 --> 00:17:45,156
At Luna's funeral.

381
00:17:46,165 --> 00:17:47,428
No, I...

382
00:17:47,500 --> 00:17:48,934
I didn't go to the funeral.

383
00:17:51,337 --> 00:17:52,930
You did.

384
00:17:54,173 --> 00:17:57,371
It was in Cold Spring a
week after the transplant.

385
00:17:59,512 --> 00:18:03,745
After the funeral, I, uh...
I saw you on that dock.

386
00:18:03,950 --> 00:18:05,612
Skipping stones.

387
00:18:06,218 --> 00:18:09,677
Well, you were trying to
skip stones. You were...

388
00:18:10,423 --> 00:18:12,119
You were really bad at it.

389
00:18:13,960 --> 00:18:17,795
So I went up and I asked
you how the stones were going.

390
00:18:19,632 --> 00:18:22,466
You said... I'll never forget.

391
00:18:24,136 --> 00:18:28,096
Your sister promised to teach
you the next time you came.

392
00:18:29,775 --> 00:18:31,744
It was the first time it hit me.

393
00:18:32,545 --> 00:18:35,037
I was only here 'cause
another girl wasn't.

394
00:18:37,984 --> 00:18:39,714
So I showed you.

395
00:18:42,622 --> 00:18:44,921
You taught me
how to skip stones.

396
00:18:45,725 --> 00:18:46,818
Yeah.

397
00:18:48,628 --> 00:18:50,256
I got <i>Mad Libs.</i>

398
00:18:50,329 --> 00:18:52,764
I just... I couldn't believe
they still publish these.

399
00:18:57,570 --> 00:18:58,731
See anything you like?

400
00:19:01,307 --> 00:19:04,539
My patient needs a study
that's going to deliver results.

401
00:19:04,610 --> 00:19:06,602
I'm more intrigued
by what I don't see.

402
00:19:06,946 --> 00:19:08,312
Definitive conclusions.

403
00:19:08,648 --> 00:19:11,550
Well, my sample size isn't large
enough for that kind of certainty,

404
00:19:11,617 --> 00:19:13,017
but I like where we're heading.

405
00:19:13,285 --> 00:19:14,753
Strong words

406
00:19:14,820 --> 00:19:16,982
from someone failing
more than he succeeds.

407
00:19:17,189 --> 00:19:20,455
It's cancer. I'll take
any wins I can get.

408
00:19:20,593 --> 00:19:23,222
And each success gets
me a little closer to a cure.

409
00:19:23,295 --> 00:19:26,925
You know what they say. Close only
counts in horseshoes and hand grenades.

410
00:19:27,166 --> 00:19:28,930
And a couple other things.

411
00:19:30,936 --> 00:19:33,235
You must know your
reputation precedes you.

412
00:19:33,305 --> 00:19:35,365
My reputation for
exceptional results?

413
00:19:35,841 --> 00:19:37,969
Your reputation for
exceptional charisma

414
00:19:38,044 --> 00:19:40,536
and aptitude for salesmanship.
And I am immune.

415
00:19:41,547 --> 00:19:43,709
Because I have
the same reputation.

416
00:19:44,150 --> 00:19:46,710
I'm only paying
attention to the numbers.

417
00:19:48,187 --> 00:19:49,815
You got your file upside down.

418
00:19:50,122 --> 00:19:52,182
Made you look.

419
00:19:57,997 --> 00:20:00,228
What would you say
to somebody who says

420
00:20:00,299 --> 00:20:03,292
you sell quixotic hope in
lieu of medical certainty?

421
00:20:03,369 --> 00:20:04,997
I'd say that someone is right.

422
00:20:05,237 --> 00:20:07,729
Clinical trials are
riskier than chemo.

423
00:20:07,807 --> 00:20:11,073
They're also the only way to
find a treatment better than chemo.

424
00:20:11,143 --> 00:20:12,668
Yeah, they're
quixotic, and, yeah,

425
00:20:12,745 --> 00:20:15,214
most of the time it doesn't
work. But when it does,

426
00:20:15,514 --> 00:20:17,278
it's gonna change the world.

427
00:20:17,349 --> 00:20:18,840
But it may never work.

428
00:20:18,918 --> 00:20:21,251
Even Don Quixote hit
a couple of windmills.

429
00:20:21,320 --> 00:20:24,552
He lunged at one and then
promptly fell off his horse.

430
00:20:24,890 --> 00:20:27,553
How soon will you know
if my patient's eligible?

431
00:20:30,563 --> 00:20:32,031
Max Goodwin.

432
00:20:32,098 --> 00:20:33,589
You're treating your boss.

433
00:20:33,666 --> 00:20:37,103
No, I'm treating my patient,
who also happens to be my friend.

434
00:20:37,837 --> 00:20:40,466
I have to warn you, I don't accept
patients based on prominence.

435
00:20:40,539 --> 00:20:42,440
The integrity of the
study is too important.

436
00:20:42,508 --> 00:20:43,601
Of course.

437
00:20:43,676 --> 00:20:46,339
And at first glance,
this is not a great fit.

438
00:20:47,413 --> 00:20:48,938
That's not a "no."

439
00:20:49,281 --> 00:20:51,773
Give me a beat, let me
get into it. I'll get back to you.

440
00:20:52,184 --> 00:20:53,846
Thank you for your honesty.

441
00:20:54,186 --> 00:20:55,552
And you for yours.

442
00:20:56,255 --> 00:20:58,247
Even though you
were a little bit mean.

443
00:21:02,261 --> 00:21:05,026
Okay. This is you.

